                </names>
                <summary>Capt. Jordan of the Mount Crawford company has resigned and Houston Hall
                    has been unanimously elected to replace him.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>For the Vindicator</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>Fras. T. Stribling</trailer>
                <names/>
                <summary>Letter informs readers that the troops at Manassas Junction are in great
                    need of medical supplies.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>Yankee Courage</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Accuses Union soldiers of being cowards who "will not stand cold steel and
                    hot lead" and claims that they only fight "bravely" when they greatly outnumber
                    their enemies.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head/>
                <origin>Examiner</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Stribling</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Dr.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>The State Convention approved the list of colonels that the Governor sent
                    them with the exception of a colonel who was in the Staunton Lunatic Asylum at
                    the time. The man's doctor, Dr. Stribling, thought that his case might be
                    curable, and so he hoped that the Convention might postpone its decision.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
